Here’s how you can teach your team why and how the updated structure of the function is better. Use this as a guide to explain the improvements in a structured and digestible way.

Why the Updated Function Structure is Better

	1.	Flexibility with Paths:
	•	Current Style: The paths are hardcoded within the function, making it rigid and tied to specific directories.
	•	Updated Style: Paths are stored in the yaml configuration file, allowing dynamic updates without changing the function. This means you can switch between paths by changing the yaml file or the model_path_key argument.
	2.	Reusability:
	•	Current Style: Separate functions exist for loading models from different paths, leading to redundancy.
	•	Updated Style: A single function now handles loading models from any path by referring to the yaml file, reducing duplication.
	3.	Maintainability:
	•	Current Style: If the paths or logic change, you need to update multiple functions, which increases the risk of inconsistencies.
	•	Updated Style: Centralizing paths in the yaml file and reusing the same function reduces the maintenance burden.
	4.	Scalability:
	•	Current Style: Adding new paths would require creating new functions.
	•	Updated Style: New paths can simply be added to the yaml file, and the same function can handle them with the model_path_key argument.
	5.	Configuration Management:
	•	Current Style: Configuration is scattered within the code, making it difficult to track and manage.
	•	Updated Style: Using a yaml file centralizes configurations, creating a single source of truth.
	6.	Clean Code Principles:
	•	Current Style: Violates the DRY (Don’t Repeat Yourself) principle by duplicating logic in two functions.
	•	Updated Style: Promotes DRY by consolidating similar logic into one flexible function.

How the Updated Function Demonstrates Best Practices

	1.	Separation of Concerns:
	•	Logic to load models is separate from the configuration (paths are externalized in yaml).
	•	This aligns with clean code principles, where functions should focus on one responsibility.
	2.	Parameterization:
	•	The model_path_key argument makes the function flexible, allowing it to load models from any specified path in the configuration.
	•	Parameterized functions are easier to test and adapt to future requirements.
	3.	Error Handling:
	•	The function validates the model_path_key and throws an error if it is invalid, providing better user feedback.
	4.	Modularity:
	•	The function uses reusable components, such as reading the yaml file and dynamically accessing paths, ensuring it can fit into a larger system seamlessly.
	5.	Future-Proof Design:
	•	The hierarchical structure of the yaml file and the modularity of the function ensure the design is ready for expansion.

How to Explain the Code to Juniors

	1.	Walkthrough the Old Approach:
	•	Explain the redundancy in having two similar functions.
	•	Highlight the challenges with hardcoding paths and how they create issues when changes are needed.
	2.	Showcase the New Function:
	•	Explain how the new function eliminates duplication by handling paths dynamically.
	•	Emphasize the use of the yaml file for configuration and the model_path_key for flexibility.
	3.	Code Example Comparison:

# Old Approach: Two separate functions
load_models_v2 <- function(mod_lookup = model_lookup) {
  for (i in 1:nrow(mod_lookup)) {
    file_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% pull(file_name)
    env_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% pull(env_name)
    assign(
      env_name,
      readRDS(here("data/api/bundle_to_api/v2_models/", file_name)),
      envir = .GlobalEnv
    )
  }
}

load_current_models <- function(mod_lookup = model_lookup) {
  for (i in 1:nrow(mod_lookup)) {
    file_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% pull(file_name)
    env_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% pull(env_name)
    assign(
      env_name,
      readRDS(here("models/trained_models/selected_model/", file_name)),
      envir = .GlobalEnv
    )
  }
}

# New Approach: One flexible function
load_models <- function(mod_lookup = model_lookup, model_path_key = "v2_path", config_file = "config/config.yaml") {
  config <- yaml::read_yaml(config_file)
  model_path <- config$model_paths[[model_path_key]]
  
  if (is.null(model_path)) {
    stop(glue::glue("Invalid model_path_key: '{model_path_key}'. Check the config file."))
  }
  
  for (i in 1:nrow(mod_lookup)) {
    file_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% dplyr::pull(file_name)
    env_name <- mod_lookup[i, ] %>% dplyr::pull(env_name)
    assign(
      env_name,
      readRDS(here::here(model_path, file_name)),
      envir = .GlobalEnv
    )
  }
  message(glue::glue("Models loaded from {model_path}."))
}


	4.	Highlight the YAML Configuration:
	•	Show how the yaml file centralizes the configuration and makes adding new paths simple.

model_paths:
  v2_path: "data/api/bundle_to_api/v2_models/"
  selected_path: "models/trained_models/selected_model/"


	5.	Real-World Example:
	•	Demonstrate loading models for two different use cases by just changing the model_path_key argument:

# Load models from v2 path
load_models(mod_lookup = model_lookup, model_path_key = "v2_path")

# Load models from selected path
load_models(mod_lookup = model_lookup, model_path_key = "selected_path")

